      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moment of Decision: The Vote on China Trade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from UAW president Stephen P Yokich disputes May 21 editorial criticizing organized labor for opposing China's entry into World Trade Organization (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Labor and the China Vote'' (editorial, May 21) concedes that ''some American workers will doubtless be hurt by foreign competition.'' You argue that American labor should make this sacrifice to help unleash the ''forces of economic globalization'' that supposedly offer great benefits to workers in China.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Labor and the China Vote'' (editorial, May 21) concedes that ''some American workers will doubtless be hurt by foreign competition.'' You argue that American labor should make this sacrifice to help unleash the ''forces of economic globalization'' that supposedly offer great benefits to workers in China.</p>
        <p>How would you explain these benefits to workers in Guangdong Province, who make handbags for Wal-Mart 12 to 14 hours a day, seven days a week? According to a recent study by the National Labor Committee, a human rights group, nearly half of these workers actually owed their employer money after several months of labor, because of deductions for food, housing, work permits and other items.</p>
        <p>Linking China's trade status to the annual review of its human rights performance remains the best tool available for creating positive change in China.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN P. YOKICH  Detroit, May 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the United Automobile Workers of America.</p>
      </block>
